My understanding of the two (and three) letter ISO codes is that
they anticipate the deployment of an ISO domain name space that
will eventually supersede the Internet domain name space (or
subsume it).  Whether this is wishful thinking or looking ahead
is anybody's guess.  I believe that before the domain system
outlives it's usefulness and is obsolete, it will become somewhat
dense unless steps are taken now to ensure reasonable sparseness.

An address like "CARLETON.CAN" could be a commercial address or
an educational one, whereas "CARLETON.EDU" could be confused betwix
Carlton College in the Midwest and Carleton University in Canada.
I don't think such scenarios are impossible.  Sufficient robustness
in the domain naming scheme exists to safeguard such conflicts,
why ignore it?

Why is Canada .CAN and not .CA?  Because Canadians don't like to
be confused with Californians, and I imagine Israeli's won't be
thrilled being confused with whatever-the-heck-you-call-someone-from
Illinois.

Actually, .CAN does exist, you just can't talk to it from outside.
This will be fixed (hopefully) soon.

I hope this doesn't confuse anyone moreso than they already are...

-Philip	(yes, I'm pap4@ai.ai.mit.edu)

